posts.raw_content:
Happy Memorial Day to all you fighters and veterans.  Veterans of conflicts and the meme-wars, all of you who are fighting for something greater than yourselves.  Thank you; you are a different breed, and this quote is for you:

“Now let's set the record straight. There's no argument over the choice between peace and war, but there's only one guaranteed way you can have peace—and you can have it in the next second—surrender.

Admittedly, there's a risk in any course we follow other than this, but every lesson of history tells us that the greater risk lies in appeasement, and this is the specter our well-meaning liberal friends refuse to face—that their policy of accommodation is appeasement, and it gives no choice between peace and war, only between fight or surrender. If we continue to accommodate, continue to back and retreat, eventually we have to face the final demand—the ultimatum. And what then—when Nikita Khrushchev has told his people he knows what our answer will be? He has told them that we're retreating under the pressure of the Cold War, and someday when the time comes to deliver the final ultimatum, our surrender will be voluntary, because by that time we will have been weakened from within spiritually, morally, and economically. He believes this because from our side he's heard voices pleading for ‘peace at any price’ or ‘better Red than dead,’ or as one commentator put it, he'd rather ‘live on his knees than die on his feet.’ **And therein lies the road to war, because those voices don't speak for the rest of us.**

You and I know and do not believe that life is so dear and peace so sweet as to be purchased at the price of chains and slavery.* If nothing in life is worth dying for, when did this begin—just in the face of this enemy? Or should Moses have told the children of Israel to live in slavery under the pharaohs? Should Christ have refused the cross? Should the patriots at Concord Bridge have thrown down their guns and refused to fire the shot heard 'round the world? The martyrs of history were not fools, and our honored dead who gave their lives to stop the advance of the Nazis didn't die in vain. Where, then, is the road to peace? Well it's a simple answer after all.

**You and I have the courage to say to our enemies, ‘There is a price we will not pay.’ ‘There is a point beyond which they must not advance.’**
…
Winston Churchill said, ‘The destiny of man is not measured by material computations. When great forces are on the move in the world, we learn we're spirits—not animals.’ And he said, ‘There's something going on in time and space, and beyond time and space, which, whether we like it or not, spells duty.’

**You and I have a rendezvous with destiny.**

**We'll preserve for our children this, the last best hope of man on earth, or we'll sentence them to take the last step into a thousand years of darkness.“**

  - Ronald Reagan, “A Time for Choosing”, 1964

It’s this mentality that created this holiday.  What the democrats do not know and cannot understand is that we are beyond peace and reconciliation with them.  For us, for Trump, that would be surrender.  We aren’t interested in that, we never have been, American men have been sacrificing for our loved ones since the 16th century, to provide them the “last best hope of man on earth.”

The democrats haven’t changed in over 60 years, except to get worse.

*Obligatory shoutout to Patrick Henry for the quote.

Grandpa Josef: WWI, emigrated from Poland to avoid the war, earned his citizenship, and was handed a letter stating his friends and neighbors had selected him… lost a lung to mustard gas. Went on to work 44 years as a machinist in a factory.


Grandpa Cas - not a veteran, but “essential industries personnel”, also a machinist, 
made tank castings in a foundry.

Dad - USN Radiman, among other things was assigned to transport UDTs.


Uncle John- lost an eye because some rocket surgeons snuck some mortar rounds into barracks and were “deactivating” them for souvenirs, and one went off as he was walking between buildings. Went to Vietnam as a civilian contractor repairing helicopter avionics and missile guidance, so technically not a Vietnam Veteran… everyone should have that one crazy cool uncle. Clot Shot got him…

Great Uncle Arcadius. You know at the end of “The Great Escape” when the group of prisoners was machine-gunned? Something similar happened to him. Made it to 100, and up to the day he died he would still, every couple days, pull a little metal frame t out of his skin.

Uncle Al, USN CPO BT 35 years. On his deathbed cursed the fact he never got his hands around the neck of the BuPers puke that got him sent to the full Water Survival Course for pilots . . . But when you are one of the top steam catapult specialists and they toss your ass ina high-performance fighter jet to get you to where there is a problem nobody else can fix…

Uncle Andy (on Mrs’ side), Merchant Marine, unsung and often denigrated Branch of service, after Vietnam became a police officer.

Thank you all who served.

posts.raw_content:
The greatness of the United States has never rested solely in its geography, its resources, or its power. Rather, it is found in the distinctive character of its people—a character forged through centuries of careful immigration, rigorous assimilation, and a shared belief in liberty, law, and responsibility. At the heart of America’s success lies a paradox: we are a nation built by immigrants, yet elevated by the challenge of becoming American.

Throughout our history, those who came here were not handed citizenship—they earned it. They left behind everything familiar to pursue something higher: a society governed by principles rather than privilege. The United States became the "cream of the crop" not by accident, but because it attracted and admitted people willing to embrace the challenge of American life: hard work, self-reliance, free expression, and civic duty. They came not just for opportunity, but to contribute to a civilization rooted in the Bill of Rights and the rule of law.

For this system to endure, immigration must be a meaningful process—not an open gate, but a deliberate passage. Mastery of the English language, understanding of our Constitution, and reverence for the liberties we guard must be prerequisites, not afterthoughts. These aren't barriers; they are the foundation of national unity and individual empowerment.

This is not a rejection of immigrants—it is a defense of what makes America worth immigrating to. We are strongest when we uphold the standard, when we ensure that becoming American means something profound. The pioneers, the engineers, the risk-takers, and the moral visionaries who shaped this country did not do so by accident—they did so because they shared a common civic culture, earned through discipline and belief in a larger idea.

To preserve our future, we must honor our past: immigration that is disciplined, principled, and proud—not only for the sake of America, but for those who truly wish to become part of its story.
